metadata.name: Rectangular Feedback Loop Trip #13
metadata.description:
Sometimes life may seem like a fight,
And we may feel like giving up on sight,
But if we hold onto hope and faith,
We'll find the strength to embrace the race.

There's no obstacle we cannot face,
When we have faith in our inner grace,
For within us lies a power so strong,
That can carry us through all that's wrong.

With every step we take, we grow,
Our spirit's light begins to glow,
And soon we'll see, that in reality,
There's nothing we can't conquer, if we truly believe.

So let's not fear what lies ahead,
Or let the doubts inside us spread,
For with trust in ourselves and each other,
We can move mountains and make dreams come further.

So let us see the world with new eyes,
With hearts that are open to the skies,
For when we believe and have faith in ourselves,
Our potential is limitless, our journey excels.


Made in Hydra Synth.

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #340
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: Archiplex — Monochrome #71
metadata.description:
Archiplex Monochrome is a long form generative project, building on the short form Archiplex series. The Archiplex Monochrome algorithm is inspired by Brutalist architecture and design, where expressive forms emerge from the use of textures, materials and structures.

Archiplex Monochrome expands on these Brutalist design elements by floating the central structure of each piece and adding random light sources, introducing unpredictability and elevation to a traditionally structured and grounded art form.

"In this series my subject is the structure: formed yet formless, gravity-bound yet weightless, reflective yet light emitting, unmovable yet malleable."

metadata.name: Elevation #56
metadata.description:
There’s so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

–

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect’s elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

–

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

–

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: Glossolalia #202
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #85
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Perpendicular Inhabitation #80
metadata.description:
'Perpendicular Inhabitation' is a generative collection exploring the relationship between the urban landscape and the human experience, particularly feelings of nostalgia and more specifically 'anemoia' : the feeling of nostalgia for a time or place that we may not have actually experienced first hand. 

Despite depicting a stylised modern architectural language, at its core the collection serves as a homage to 1980s Japan, an era of unprecedented prosperity that left a lasting impression on the music and artwork of the time. Through the use of carefully created palettes and composition, the outputs intend to evoke feelings of optimism, while guiding viewers to consider why the essence of this era is so alluring in the present day as it continues to influence and inspire contemporary art.

The use of exaggerated perpendicular verticals, as well as the heavily foreshortened mountain ranges present in some outputs, convey a sense of hope and possibility for the future. What does it feel like to hope and dream in the city? To look up and be filled with a sense of wonder from the built environment around you?

This project has been created with print in mind at a ratio of 3:4

It is recommended to examine your outputs at full size in order to enjoy them to the fullest.

You are encouraged to return often to notice things you may not have seen previously.

Generated with code using p5.js

Images are generated at 2400 x 3200 px. 

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

Depending on the complexity of each output, please wait up to 10 seconds for the image generation to complete.

metadata.name: FORMAT #23
metadata.description:
A generative animated artwork by Unruly Unroll, 2022.  
Custom HTML, JavaScript and GLSL code.

This artwork is responsive and the canvas will adapt to the size and orientation of the browser window.

Interaction on desktop :
- Press the 'SPACE' key to pause/unpause the animation.
- Press the 'S' key to save the current frame to a PNG file.  
- Press the 'F' key or double-click to switch to full screen mode.  
- Press the 'ESC' key to exit full screen mode.  

Interaction on mobile :
- Tap the screen to pause/unpause the animation.
- Double-tap the screen to switch to full screen mode.  
- Tap the back button to exit full screen mode.

@UnrulyUnroll

metadata.name: pantonX.2 #93
metadata.description:
pantonX.2

I am a visual artist and have worked in the field of coding since the early years of processing.
Always loved geometric and minimalist art, bauhaus, De Stijl, Piet Mondrian, Ellsworth Kelly, Imi Knoebel -- just to name a few -- and last but not least Verner Panton, have had a big influence on my artistic work.

pantonX.2 is my second fxhash release. it's coded in p5js.
I set up a wider random range for the color arrays and the division structure, so that a 200x drop would have enough variation for not getting boring. 

"s" key is for saving

metadata.name: On the Grid #12
metadata.description:
On the Grid is a generative art project resulting in a unique 16/9 format world map.

This project is inspired by a 114cm x 76cm Lego world map that I created in real life. The coordinates of the continents are transpositions from this first project.

It is made using SVG and Vanilla JS with no libraries.

I hope you enjoy discovering On the Grid and minting your own unique world map.

Thanks for collecting!

In live mode:
- 's': save as PNG (3200×1800)
- 'v': save as SVG  
- 'f': open in full screen mode

metadata.name: StairWaves #138
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)
